name: 4,5-dimethoxy-3-iodobenzaldehyde
Reason: 4,5-dimethoxy-3-iodobenzaldehyde has a melting point that we will compare to benzene, which has a melting point of 5.5°C (according to the CRC Handbook of Chemistry and Physics, 49th Edition, 1968-1969). The basic unit for our comparison will be benzene. The structural modifications we need to consider are the presence of a methoxy group, which can increase the melting point due to additional molecular weight and hydrogen bonding potential. The iodine atom also introduces a significant dipole moment, which can contribute to intermolecular interactions and raise the melting point. The methoxy group can be estimated to add approximately +5°C due to additional molecular weight and hydrogen bonding potential. The iodine atom can be estimated to add approximately +10°C due to the significant dipole moment it introduces.
